companions of the lens star because they can, depending on the planetary mass and position, perturb the ring-like image of the source star at times near the peak amplification (1–5). They complement events of low magnification that also provide substantial sensitivity for detecting extrasolar planets when “caustic crossings” occur (6–9). For both detection methods, the sensitivity to low-mass planets is enhanced in events with small (that is, main-sequence) source stars (2, 5, 8).
